                <h1>The Anatomy of an Adviser</h1>
                
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/madaline-perez">Madaline Perez</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">February 5, 2009 | 4:00am EST</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/02/anatomy-adviser" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/02/anatomy-adviser&amp;text=The Anatomy of an Adviser" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=The%20Anatomy%20of%20an%20Adviser%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2009%2F02%2Fanatomy-adviser" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>Everyone's heard the stories. </p>
<p>The distant ones.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>"There are too many students and too few advisers," senior Yessenia Castillo complains. "When you walk into the office they don't even know who you are, even though you were there just the other day. They don't look you up by name, but by your number. That is who you are to your academic adviser."</p>
<p>The aloof ones.</p>
<p>"My pre-major adviser, he was a great guy, but he was a little too lovey-dovey," senior Stephanie Okpala recalls. "He was like, 'Just explore your options.' And he made me feel as if I could do whatever I wanted for the next few years. But once I got a hold of what I wanted to do, I realized I should've been on track immediately following freshman year, if not freshman year."</p>
<p>The glass-half-empty ones.</p>
<p>"I feel like they try to discourage you when you're doing badly instead of filling you with hope and that's not what an adviser is supposed to do," Castillo continues. "They're supposed to give you options."</p>
<p>And just the bureaucracy of it all.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>"It was a little annoying to me because I'm one of those people who knows where they're going and what they want to do, and I don't feel like I need an adviser, so it's more of an annoyance that I have to even go to academic advising," Okpala says. "It's a little inconvenient."</p>
<p>Advisers don't necessarily have the best reputations on campus.</p>
<p>But there are the good as well.</p>
<p>"My advising has been amazing. My freshman adviser was very engaged, but I know that it wasn't the case for a lot of people," sophomore Danny Mammo says. "It sounds too good to be true, but she really was amazing, and I still keep in touch with her even though I have another adviser."</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
